{"key":"processedPost-11270015","value":{"id":11270015,"first":11269157,"last":11278203,"when":1255875059,"utime":"10/18/09 05:10 PM","cleanedPost":"Correct.&nbsp; Gypsum is not a pH buffer.&nbsp; Gypsum is used to supply calcium and sulfur.&nbsp; <br />Oyster shells, egg shells, calcium carbonate, etc., are all piss-poor buffers for casings because they take a month or more to become effective, even when powdered.&nbsp; That's why you want to use hydrated lime.&nbsp; It's water soluble and raises pH immediately.<br />NEVER USE BAKING SODA IN YOUR CASING LAYERS!&nbsp; It's not an appropriate way to raise pH, and is highly toxic to mycelium.<br />Substrates don't need a pH correction.&nbsp; Mushroom mycelium actually prefers an acidic pH and grows fastest when the pH is between 5 and 6.&nbsp; However, since casing layers usually don't fully colonize, we buffer them to a pH of about 8 to help prevent mold spores from germinating.&nbsp; The live mushroom mycelium can tolerate a high pH, but it's hard for spores to germinate.<br />RR"}}